	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EBA reduces ACP exports, study claims</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A paper by two German academics from the 2010 German Development Economics Conference in Hanover has been published, and finds that there was a negative effect of the EBA regime on the exports of ACP less developed countries (LDCs) in the 10 years up to 2005. When account is also taken of the effects of aid, however, the impact on exports was positive. The authors conclude that the latter finding supports ‘an EU development strategy that includes both sorts of assistance, aid and trade preferences.’</p><p>Using a gravity model, the study considers exports from the ACP to the EU15 over the period 1995-2005 to examine whether the EBA regime has had discernable effects on the exports of those ACP states that are eligible for it because they are LDCs. They find that ‘the EBA agreement does not seem to foster exports; it actually decreases their value in the absence of additional aid. In contrast, the interaction effect between EBA and ODA turns out to be positive and highly significant as a determinant of exports from the ACP LDCs to the EU15.’ One overall conclusion is that ‘it is questionable whether non-reciprocal preference schemes should be used as a replacement to aid flows.’</p><p>The finding of the positive effect of aid on exports strikes a chord with an IMF analysis, but the negative one on EBA is in contradiction. The IMF argues that increased trade will be a critical element in meeting the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). It considers that one of the steps needed to achieve this is ‘to close an “infrastructure gap” and address climate change’, both of which ‘face massive financing needs’, but that another is to ‘extend duty-free, quota-free coverage to all products from LDCs without delay’. The two studies agree that much more needs to be done to boost LDC exports. The IMF analysis points out that despite accounting for nearly 1% of global GDP, LDCs account for under 0.5% of global non-oil exports ‘a figure that, in contrast to the dynamic trade growth of other developing countries, has been virtually unchanged over the past 15 years.’</p><p>Both of the measures recommended by the IMF are part of an agenda it puts forward of ‘Fifteen trade actions that could help to achieve the MDGs’. Full implementation of this agenda, it argues, could increase annual exports of the LDCs by US$10 billion or more, with additional benefits for other low income countries (LICs). The agenda requires actions not only by the developed countries but also by the emerging markets and by the LDCs and LICs. In addition to completing the Doha Round, other items include making rules of origin simpler and more flexible, and increasing ‘cumulation’ (i.e. joint processing by two or more preference recipients).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>K. Gradeva and I. Martínez-Zarzoso, ‘The role of the Everything But Arms trade preferences regime in the EU development strategy’, Verein für Socialpolitik, Proceedings of the 2010 German Development Economics Conference in Hanover, Series No. 42, September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://econstor.eu/bitstream/10419/39993/1/324_gradeva.pdf" target="_self">http://econstor.eu/bitstream/10419/39993/1/324_gradeva.pdf</a></p><p>IMF staff, ‘Reaching the MDGs: an action plan for trade’, position paper, 16 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/spn/2010/spn1014.pdf" target="_self">http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/spn/2010/spn1014.pdf</a></p><p><i>Commod@frica</i>, ‘Rapprochement d’entreprises entre le Soudan et le Brésil – plusieurs accords signés, notamment dans le sucre’, 27 September 2010 (in French)</p><p>
<a href="http://www.commodafrica.com/fr/actualites/matieres_premieres/soudanbresil" target="_self">http://www.commodafrica.com/fr/actualites/matieres_premieres/soudanbresil</a></p><p><i>Reuters</i>, ‘Sudan signs $500 million deals with Brazil-sugar exec’, 26 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/article677113.ece/Sudan-signs--500-mln-deals-with-Brazil-sugar-exec" target="_self">http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/article677113.ece/Sudan-signs--500-mln...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As with all models, the conclusions drawn by the EBA study depend critically on the assumptions that have been made (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/content/view/full/857" target="_self">Costs of the CARIFORUM EPA claimed in study to be “modest”</a>’). But it is also important to consider exactly what is being measured when deciding whether or not the findings are surprising and the conclusions drawn are sound. By focusing only on ACP LDCs and on the period before the banana, rice and sugar elements of EBA were fully implemented, the researchers minimised the likelihood that their work would uncover any positive effects of EBA. Given that access terms to the EU market for most products were identical under EBA and Cotonou during this period, there would have been no reason for traders to switch forms. Things may change if the EBA preferences on sugar and rice encourage more investment. The announcement that Sudan’s Kenana sugar refinery has signed two deals with Brazil’s Dedini to provide machinery and equipment to double the size of its ethanol plant in Sudan and to set up a new biodiesel operation is an indication of what might happen more widely in future.</p><p>The finding that EBA had a negative impact (rather than no impact at all) is more surprising, but the researchers recognise that this is a less favourable finding than in most (although not all) previous studies which have ‘showed a modest but throughout a constant positive influence of the EBA scheme on the exports of LDCs’. Although they offer some explanations for this difference, the implications of small variations between study results should not be exaggerated.</p><p>The IMF recommendation for more cumulation between preference beneficiaries comes at a time when EU provisions for the ACP have deteriorated sharply. Exporters in both Kenya and Swaziland have been adversely affected by the split in the ACP between (I)EPA signatories and non-signatories and by the new rules for customs administrative cooperation agreements to be in place between countries before they can cumulate.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
